   {:e #blake3 "c0a323af1813532fcc75f1e3b4ff2d6a919dbf44a2fa7216cf150cb6ae3350ed" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-sum-sq; Session entity: :session/s-1774491518; Session entity: :config/concept-join-threshold; Session entity: :config/concept-sigmoid-temperature; Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-count; Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-sum\nThe autoprompt/budget.go implements attention budget decay (APP-INV-035): k*_eff starts at BaseBudget=12 and decreases by 1 for every Step=5 conversation turns, with Floor=3 as minimum. Token target linearly interpolates from 2000 tokens at k*=12 to 300 tokens at k*=3. Attenuation ranges 0.0 (full guidance) to 0.75 (max attenuation at depth>=45). The package has tests (9.5KB) but only 2 source files (budget.go + types.go) — the actual prompt assembly appears to have been extracted or never implemented here.; The storage package (internal/storage/) uses a 30-table normalized SQLite schema (APP-ADR-005) with 5 core files totaling ~125KB. Models map 1:1 to tables: SpecIndex, SourceFile, Section, Invariant, ADR. The schema.go file defines all CREATE TABLE statements as a const string SchemaSQL, with CHECK constraints for enums (source_type, file_role) and proper FK references. Content-addressable hashing (SHA-256) is used for deduplication on sections and invariants.; Heavy *sql.DB coupling: 63 Go files across 30+ packages import database/sql directly. Nearly every analysis function takes *sql.DB as its first argument (Analyze, Record, Check, ComputeState etc). There are only 3 interfaces in the entire codebase (Provider, Check, Applier) — almost no abstraction boundaries. The storage package is not a proper data access layer; it is a bag of SQL query functions that every other package calls directly. This creates a deeply coupled architecture where every package depends on the concrete SQLite schema.; The events package implements a three-stream event sourcing architecture (APP-ADR-015). Stream 1=Discovery (ideas, questions), Stream 2=Specification (parse, validate, drift), Stream 3=Implementation (issues, status). Events use an immutable append-only envelope (APP-INV-020) with SHA-256 content hashing, causal predecessor tracking (Causes field, APP-INV-074), and schema versioning (APP-INV-072). Event IDs are date-prefixed random hex for collision avoidance.; Testing gap: 25 of 39 internal packages have test files — 14 packages are completely untested. Notably untested: bundle, cascade, diff, exemplar, impact, implorder, oplog, progress, query, renderer, skeleton, state. Several of these (cascade, impact, query) perform non-trivial analysis. The tested packages include the heavy-hitters: storage (22KB tests), parser (24KB tests), triage (26KB tests), consistency, materialize, witness. The coverage is concentrated in the verification pipeline (consistency, witness, validator) while the operational pipeline (discover, absorb, refine) has thinner coverage.; The cascade package performs change-impact analysis: given a spec element ID, it traces through module_relationships (maintains/interfaces/implements/adjacent) to find all affected modules and domains. It uses a cascading type-probe pattern (try invariant, then ADR, then gate) rather than a polymorphic lookup. The depth parameter (1-5, default 3) is accepted but unused — reserved for future multi-hop cascade. The invariant_registry provides ownership mapping. This is single-hop blast radius analysis, not true transitive closure.; The triage package implements the spec fitness function F(S) as a weighted 6-signal combination (APP-INV-069). Weights are hardcoded constants (not configurable) to prevent gaming: validation=0.20, coverage=0.20, drift=0.20, challenge_hp=0.15, contradictions=0.15, issue_backlog=0.10. RankDeficiencies computes steepest-descent direction by sorting gaps by estimated delta-F. IsFixpointFitness checks for F(S)=1.0. This is a direct precursor to braids acquisition function alpha=E[delta-F(S)]/cost.; Naming anomaly: two near-identical packages — internal/discover (6 files, classify/context/thread/record) and internal/discovery (4 files, events/tasks/models). Both deal with the discovery phase of the bilateral cycle but split inconsistently. discover handles recording and context assembly for the discovery session, while discovery handles issue/task management (18KB tasks.go) and event emission. This is a code-smell indicating incomplete domain decomposition — the bounded context for the discovery phase leaked across two packages with overlapping models.go files.; The consistency package implements a 5-tier contradiction detection engine (Tiers 2-6): graph-based (typed edges, governance overlap), SAT (gophersat propositional encoding), heuristic (polarity/quantifier/numeric rules + LSI), SMT (Z3 subprocess, APP-ADR-038), and LLM-as-judge (Anthropic API). Each tier produces Contradiction structs with confidence scores, evidence, and resolution hints. The zero-false-positive invariant (APP-INV-019) governs all tiers. Notable: 9 distinct ConflictTypes from governance_overlap to semantic_tension.; The parser package (20 files, ~90KB) handles DDIS spec parsing with monolith/modular polymorphism (APP-ADR-010). ManifestData struct defines the spec shape: modules with cross-references (maintains, interfaces, implements, adjacent), an invariant_registry, context_budget with reasoning_reserve, and constitution system/domains. Each spec element type (invariants, ADRs, negspecs, gates, performance, verification, whynot, glossary, examples, xref) has its own parser file — highly modular. The patterns.go file suggests regex-based extraction of structured blocks from markdown." :op :assert}
